==Old English==
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''[[tehun]]'' from Indo-European ''*dekṃ-'' ‘ten’.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''tiān'', Old High German [[zehan]] (German [[zehn]]), Old Saxon [[tehan]] (Dutch [[tien]]), Old Norse ''tíu'' (Icelandic [[tíu]], Norwegian [[ti]], Swedish [[tio]]), Gothic [[𐍄𐌰𐌹𐌷𐌿𐌽]]; and, outside the Germanic languages, with Sanskrit [[दश]], Greek [[δέκα]], Latin [[decem]], Old Irish [[deich]] (Irish [[deich]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /ti:en/
===Cardinal number===
'''tīen'''

# [[ten]]

===Alternative spellings===
'''tīen''' or '''tīene''' are West Saxon forms, also represented by Anglian '''tēn''' or '''tēne'''.

===Ordinal number===
''[[tēoþa]]''

